Analysis of Contributions towards Presidential Campaign in 2016 in California

by Rajat Gupta

This dataset looks at the Financial Contributions made to the presidential campaign for the U.S. presidential election in 2016 in the State of California. The data is provided by the Federal Election Commission and includes information about the donor, the amount contributed and the receiving candidate. Extra information about the individuals party affiliation and gender have also been added.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The data has been divided into various columns providing information about the donor, the candidate to whom the donation has been made and when the donation was made. This information has been spread across 20 variables of which 17 variables are ordered factors, only one is a continous variable (contb_receipt_amt).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features of interest involve looking at the relation between the amount donated, number of contibutions and the characterstics (occupation, employer) of the donor. It will also be interesting looking at different candidates and analysing the sources of their donations.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

The information about party affiliation, candidate gender, contributed amount, time at which the contribution was made, all lend themselves to the analysis being performed and will help in determining if any correlation exists between different variables.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Two new variables describing the party affiliation and the gender of the candidate were added to help in analysing the data. Data for the creation of both the variables was achieved through the Wikipedia page for each of the candidates.

This data is required to analyse the variation in donations made according to the party affiliation and candidate gender to determine possible donor preferences.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

The data has a lot of empty entries specially in the election_tp, contbr_employer variables.

The variable, contbr_employer was cleaned to care of over abbreviated employer names and empty values. However, complete cleaning was not possible due to high number of records and presence of unique entries each following a different standard.

Also, while analysing the amount contributed, only values with positive contb_receipt_amt were considered because a negative value represented a refund made back to the donor which doesnt reflect a donation.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset

Multiple analysis were performed which included studying the relation between gender and amount donated, identifying occupations and employers who have contributed the largest single amounts to the campaigns, the variation in amounts donated depending on the Candidate among each major political party and looking at different correlations between various variables.

It was interesting to see that female candidates, had a higher number of large donations compared to their male counter parts. This was mainly due to contributions made toward one candidate (Clinton, Hillary Rodham). It was also seen to no surprise that the large contributions came from indivduals who had high ranking occupations such as CEO, founder, president, etc. An analysis of the relation between total contributions made and the total amount donated to a particular candidate showed a very strong correlation exhibited by the Pearson Correlation Coefficient.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

As the main variable being analysed is contb_receipt_amt i.e.the amount contributed for each entry, all relations are generated with respect to this variable.

We saw that females generated more money than their male counterparts and having higher contributions would increase your chances of generating greater money. Also, Pearsons Correlation coefficient suggested that greater the number of donations made in a day, greater is the amount generated.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relation established was the one between the total number of donations made to a candidate and the total amount generated by that candidate.

Lets look at the variation in the amount donated per person depending on the employer for the top 5 candidates.

#We will be making two plots, which will make data visualization easier.

#Employers listed on first graph
gp_one <- c("NONE", "HOMEMAKER", "NOT EMPLOYED", "SELF EMPLOYED", "RETIRED")

#Employers listed on second graph
gp_two <- c("APPLE", "GOOGLE", "UCLA", "STATE OF CALIFORNIA", 
            "STANFORD UNIVERSITY")

#Candidates receiving most donations, as seen earlier
cand_name_emp <- c("Clinton, Hillary Rodham", "Sanders, Bernard", 
                   "Trump, Donald J.","Cruz, Rafael Edward 'Ted'", 
                   "Rubio, Marco")

#Function to get the total number of donations per candidate and amount given 
#per donation for each employer

get_data <- function(employers, candidates, dataframe){
  cand_employer_data <- ddply(dataframe, c("contbr_employer","cand_nm"),
                              c("nrow"))
  
  gp_data <- subset(cand_employer_data, contbr_employer %in% employers)
  gp_data <- subset(gp_data, cand_nm %in% candidates)
  
  sums <- aggregate(Data$contb_receipt_amt,by=list(Data$cand_nm,
                                                 Data$contbr_employer),FUN=sum)
  sums <- subset(sums, (Group.1 %in% candidates)&(Group.2 %in% employers))
  
  gp_data$per_person <- sums$x/gp_data$nrow
  return (gp_data)
}

gp_one_data <- get_data(gp_one,cand_name_emp, Data)
gp_two_data <- get_data(gp_two,cand_name_emp, Data)

We can see from the analysis, that Rubio, Marco received the greatest Contribution per person for most of the cases. In a lot of the cases minimum contribution per person was received by Clinton, Hillary Rodham who we have seen received the most donations and the greatest amount in previous analysis. Thus, this greater contribution per person can be because of lesser number of contributions made to Rubio, Marco. Thus, we look at total contributions made by individuals working for each of these employers to the candidates. To plot these values we use a log scale on the y axis,

The two graphs give very different results. The second one confirms the hypothesis stated that Clinton, Hillary Rodham got the most amount of donations because of her larger number of donations, but in the first plot we see that Sanders, Bernard, Rubio, Marco and Trump, Donald J. received a total greater contribution than Clinton, Hillary Rodham for some values.

For these values, lets look at the total contributions made and the average contribution per person,

investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

Two different analysis were performed here, first we looked at the sources of donations for the top receiving candidate and found that two cities are major contributors to this amount.

The other analysis examined the possiblity of a relation between employers of the donor and the candidate receiving the donation.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

It was interesting to see that donors who work for certain employers deviated from the consensus top receiving candidate and having greatest number of contributions from a particular group is not a guarantee that the total contribution received from that group will be the greatest. Also, if popularity is measured by the number of donations received, we have identified certain groups (Employers under the categories, Not Employed, None, Homemaker & Retired) which have different preferences from the overall consensus.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This plot looks at the cities from where the maximum donations were received, it can be seen clearly that most of these cities are located along the edges/ coast of the region. This implies that these locations might be densely populated and it makes sense to spend more time and resources campaigning in these cities in the future.

Plot Two

Description Two

From the above plot, it can be seen that the candidates who received the most number (and amount) of donations have a lower median and quartile values, with a lot of outliers as most of these donations are smaller amounts which drives the median and quartile values low. This trend is consistent for candidates of both the major political parties.

Plot Three

Description Three

From the above graph we see that individuals working for certain employers have preferences different from the state consensus (if popularity is taken as the number of donations received by a candidate). We see that individuals working for None, Retired, Not Employed and Homemaker prefer different candidates to the one most popular in the state (Clinton, Hillary Rodham). This can serve as an important factor in formulating proposed policies and targetting new donors which all contribute to being successful in an election.

Reflection

This dataset contained information about the donations received by candidates for the 2016 U.S. Presidential Election from the state of California.

As, there was really only one continous variable in amount donated, analysis revolved around its variation with different groups like political party, candidate name, city of the donor , employer information & occupation of the donor. It was interesting to note that the analysis kept pointing towards a single main leader within the candidates (Clinton, Hillary Rodham) which received the most number and the highest amount of donations.

Variations in the amount donated to candidates revealed that more the number of donations, there is a greater likelihood that the median donation received is lesser. We were also able to identify certain groups that have preferences which are different from the overall trend. This is important for targetting new vote banks and generating more funds for the campaign.

This analysis could have been more detailed if, some extra information like age of donors & donor genders was available as candidate preferences vary a lot with age and donor gender might have a bearing on the candidate of choice. The conclusions discussed in the analysis are based on certain assumptions like popularity is a measured by number of donations received by a candidate. Thus, care should be taken while drawing conclusions.

This data could be analysed against the data for the Presidential Election held in 2012 to look at variations in contributions by cities, the differences in dates when these contributions were made and looking at the variation in funds generated between the two major political parties.
